<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
Diagnosis features of males and females are discussed in 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. kurunegala" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="kurunegala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">M. kurunegala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. Males with angularly bent embolus and furcate conductor (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 25" captionStartId="F25" captionText="Figure 25. Merizocera peraderiya sp. nov., holotype male. A Bulb, dorsal view B bulb, dorsal view, embolus and conductor distorted C palp, prolateral view D palp, retrolateral view. Abbreviations: CO = conductor, CP = cymbial protrusion, EM = embolus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.961.53058.figure25" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/443251" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">25B</figureCitation>
). Females with a pair of twisted spermathecae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 26" captionStartId="F26" captionText="Figure 26. Merizocera peraderiya sp. nov., holotype male and paratype female. A Endogyne, dorsal view B female epigastric area, ventral view C male habitus, dorsal view D female habitus, dorsal view E female habitus, ventral view. Abbreviation: SP = spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.961.53058.figure26" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/443252" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">26A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
